Identity theft occurs when someone hijacks a consumer's personal identifying information such as a name, address, credit card or Social Security number and uses the information to open new charge accounts or purchase merchandise.
Twenty-two states have passed laws since 1996 making identity theft a crime.
The hearing was held to discuss the effectiveness of the Identity Theft and Assumption Deterrence law passed in 1998 to help officials combat the growing problem of pilfered identities.
